snippet.textDisplay:
As a biologist, I can explain why antibiotics don't work on viruses. To put it simply, antibiotics work by disrupting at least one natural function of the cell. Well, viruses don't have these normal functions for themselves and have to hijack cells - they're effectively genetic bullets, harmless (relatively) until put in a gun (cell) and fired. Because they don't have those cell functions, antibiotics pass right by them - they don't even target the virus in the cells, just the cells themselves. This is why it is recommended that you do NOT load up on antibiotics, and not just because they don't work. You could potentially destroy cells vital for your continued survival if you load up.

At the core, there is no true anti-viral cure, none man-made anyway. Everything done to deal with viruses is meant to bolster your immunity against them. Relieving symptoms can go a ways towards helping you fight it off. After all, by fighting the virus (or any disease, really), your body can lose track of maintaining normal functions, and this can cause disruptions in actions that could be vital to keeping your body supplied with nutrients and energy to fight. Being able to stay properly fed can go a long way (and yes, fluid intake is a part of being properly fed) so intentionally starving yourself is easily one of the dumbest things you can do for your recovery. Of course, relieving symptoms isn't enough for your body to cure itself - it just helps.

TL;DR Your assumptions are wrong, stay clean, stay fed, stay isolated as much and as long as you can (there's only so much isolating you can do on your own), and you should be able to ride it out. There is no guarantee, but you will maximize your odds if you do these things.
